{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"45e06236-35e7-4293-9913-5f0a30eaa184","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed how **test IDs** are computed. The fully qualified test ID now includes different metadata, so Azure DevOps sees them as entirely new tests. There's no built-in migration path — history is effectively reset.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it no longer carries test-specific properties like `TestName`. Previously it leaked the name of whichever test happened to trigger initialization (non-deterministic). Now it throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\n**Fix for your code** — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Move per-test logic to [TestInitialize] instead\n}\n```\n\n## Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallelization** | Default scope changed; tests may now run in parallel where they didn't before. Set `[Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` explicitly if needed. |\n| **Timeout** | `[Timeout]` now applies to the test method only, not setup/cleanup. |\n| **Assert.ThrowsException** | Async overloads are stricter about returned tasks. |\n| **DataRow display** | `[DataRow]` display names changed, also affecting test IDs. |\n| **ClassCleanup timing** | Runs after the last test in the class by default (was end-of-assembly in some v3 configs). |\n| **Constructor DI** | v4 supports constructor injection; test classes with unexpected constructors may behave differently. |\n\nThe biggest silent risk is **parallelization** — if your tests share static state, you may see intermittent failures that didn't exist before.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ec8f0f7e-c503-49e2-a284-bac30d1ad641","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have the full context. The user upgraded to MSTest v4.1.0 and has:\n\n1. Tests appearing as new in Azure DevOps (lost history)\n2. `TestContext.TestName` throwing in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nLet me provide guidance on these known MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Test ID changes**: MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed (fully qualified names changed), which causes Azure DevOps to treat them as new tests. This is a known breaking change.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a \"class-level\" context that doesn't have test-specific information like `TestName` (since no specific test is running yet). Accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException`. This is by design — previously it would return the name of the first test that triggered class initialization, which was non-deterministic.\n\n\n3. **Other breaking changes to watch for**: `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` now require parameterless constructors or the new dependency injection pattern, test parallelization defaults shifted, `DeploymentItem` works differently, assembly-level attributes behave differently, and `TestContext` properties aren't automatically populated via setters in some cases.","outputTokens":836,"requestId":"BD0E:86E8:1FC53F2:24047B9:6A07D5CE"},"id":"f1242284-2cbc-4c54-aae3-6446f03c9d8c","timestamp":"2026-05-16T02:26:40.304Z","parentId":"bab32994-3b52-4f3c-8a7f-f9c88958027c"}
